                <h2>Lead with the Conclusion: Concentration Beats Diversification in Cold Start</h2>
<p>A typical mistake many cross-border e-commerce operators make in budget allocation is: hearing about a channel's "red ocean period," they rush to open accounts and top up for testing; seeing competitors perform well on TikTok, they want a share too. The result is often spending a little on every channel, but not enough on any single channel to accumulate sufficient data. The ad system hasn't yet learned your target audience before the budget is exhausted.</p>
<p>In the process of serving numerous cross-border e-commerce teams, Yiyu Media has seen too many such cases: a home goods independent site opened Meta, Google, TikTok, and Pinterest simultaneously, with a daily budget of $100 for each channel. After three weeks, Meta finally started gaining traction, but by then the other three channels had already burned nearly $10,000 with almost zero ROI. More embarrassing is that Meta's traction was due to luck hitting a viral creative—the next creative may or may not replicate this success.</p>
<p><strong>The correct approach in the cold start phase is: first get the model running on one platform, then consider expansion.</strong></p>
<h2>Three Phases of Budget Allocation</h2>
<h3>Phase One: Validation Period (First 30 Days)</h3>
<p>The core goal of this phase is to verify the feasibility of "traffic to conversion," not pursuing ROI.</p>
<p>Budget allocation suggestions:<br />
- One main platform (Meta/Google): 70-80%<br />
- Backup test channel: 20-30%<br />
- New channel exploration: Not yet invested</p>
<p>Yiyu Media's recommendation: if your product is a standard product with medium price point ($50-200), prioritize Meta because its audience targeting is more precise; if it's non-standard with high price point ($200+), Google's search traffic typically has better conversion rates.</p>
<p><strong>The key metric isn't ROI, but "how quickly can you accumulate 500 conversions."</strong> Only with this data volume can the platform algorithm truly learn your target users, making subsequent scaling meaningful.</p>
<h3>Phase Two: Optimization Period (Days 31-60)</h3>
<p>After the first month of testing, you should have developed 1-2 well-performing ad creatives and audience combinations. Goals for this phase:</p>
<ol>
<li>Double the budget for main creatives</li>
<li>Start testing second-tier channels (like TikTok short videos)</li>
<li>Establish routine creative A/B testing mechanisms</li>
</ol>
<p>Budget can be adjusted to: main platform 65%, second platform 25%, test reserve 10%. Pay special attention to "balance alerts" and "multi-account management" during this phase to avoid well-performing ads suddenly pausing due to account limits or insufficient balance.</p>
<h3>Phase Three: Scale Period (After Stabilization)</h3>
<p>When a channel's CPA (Cost Per Acquisition) remains stable for two consecutive weeks and the LTV/CAC ratio exceeds 3, consider increasing investment and expanding to new channels. The budget allocation logic at this point: <strong>70% to validated mature channels, 30% to test channels.</strong></p>
<h2>A Common Misconception to Avoid</h2>
<p>Many operators, after opening accounts, are eager to activate all channels, thinking "we'll just keep them open—no cost if we don't spend." However, the hidden costs of chaotic multi-account management are often underestimated:</p>
<ul>
<li>Multiple platforms require separate reconciliation, doubling financial reconciliation workload</li>
<li>Different platforms have different policy compliance requirements; one account issue may affect others</li>
<li>Creatives need customization for different platforms, scattering energy</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Yiyu Media's suggestion: it's not about having many channels, but about having the right ones.</strong> The more accounts you open, the exponentially more complex operations become, while conversion efficiency may not improve correspondingly.</p>
<h2>Final Thoughts</h2>
<p>The underlying logic of budget allocation is simple: <strong>in phases of highest uncertainty, concentrate resources on the highest certainty matters.</strong> The certainty in the cold start phase is choosing 1-2 mainstream platforms and giving them enough budget and time for the ad system to complete its learning. Once the model stabilizes, then discuss channel expansion, creative optimization, and ROI improvement.</p>
<p>If you're struggling with multi-account management, balance alerts, or financial reconciliation, welcome to learn about Yiyu Media's overseas advertising account management services. We can take over these operational chores so you can focus on what truly matters.</p>
